{{other uses|Pearly Gates (disambiguation)}}
[[File:Hans Memling 017.jpg|thumb|right|130px|''The Blessed at the gate to heaven with St. Peter'' by [[Hans Memling]].]]
'''Pearly gates''' is an informal name for the gateway to [[Heaven (Christianity)|Heaven]] according to some [[List of Christian denominations|Christian denominations]]. It is inspired by the description of the [[New Jerusalem]] in {{bibleref|Revelation|21:21|31}}: "The twelve gates were twelve pearls, each gate being made from a single pearl."<ref>{{cite book |last=Lang |first=J. Stephen |authorlink= |chapter=59: Imagine the Size of Those Oysters |title=What the Good Book Didn't Say: Popular Myths and Misconceptions About the Bible |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qputB4k78JQC&pg=PA185#v=onepage&q=pearly%20gates&f=false |year=2003 |publisher=Citadel Press |location= |isbn=9780806524603 |page=185}}</ref>

The image of the gates in popular culture is a set of large gold, white or wrought-iron gates in the clouds, guarded by [[Saint Peter]] (the keeper of the "[[Keys of the kingdom|keys to the kingdom]]"). Those not fit to enter heaven are denied entrance at the gates, and descend into [[Hell]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Ferguson |first=Everett |authorlink=Everett Ferguson |title=The Church of Christ: A Biblical Ecclesiology for Today |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kVqRaiPlx88C&pg=PA53#v=onepage&q=%22doorkeeper%20of%20heaven%22&f=false |year=1996 |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |location= |isbn=9780802841896 |page=53 |quote=The passage moves from a building, to gates, to keys. A popular image has Peter as the doorkeeper of heaven, deciding admission through the pearly gates to each person at death. This understanding of Peter goes back to an early medieval interpretation that identified Peter with a figure in Germanic mythology who was the porter of heaven.}}</ref> In some versions of this imagery, Peter looks up the deceased's name in a book, before opening the gate.

